slides.title: Overview
slides.text: Mapping the news articles it became clear that newspapers portrait the Uber controversy from many different angles and with different settings for the knowledge production to the public. Four main clusters was discovered each represented a distinct discourse within the controversy.

slides.title: Business and economy
slides.text: This cluster show the Uber controversy from a business and cooperative angle. They discuss venture capital as a possible merging economy. The stock market see this merging economy as a effect of the financial crises. The competing business sees Uber as a threat to licensed taxi drivers, e.g black taxis in London.

slides.title: Licensed taxi drivers vs. Uber drivers
slides.text: On a labor market level the controversy is heated between licensed taxi drivers and Uber drivers. The ride-sharing companies and the uber drivers see ridesharing as a democratic development for the labor market, whereas the licensed taxi driver see it as a threat for their livelihood.

slides.title: Platform and social network
slides.text: Within this cluster tech startups and programmers discuss the development of the original app program to create the best world wide platform to use on a local level. These companies reach their customers through social network and cool features with a promise of potential profit.

slides.title: Public and legislatetive sector
slides.text: In this cluster we get a view into how the social and political institutions and large tech companies address the Uber controversy. The discussion is centered around health care, union memberships, labor law, payroll taxes and full time employment. One example is the mention of Obamacare, which make it easier and more affordable to get a health insurance even though the uber driver isn't a licensed work.
